## 2. Structural Anatomy of an HTTP Request

An HTTP request sent from a client consists of three primary components: the **Request Line**, **Headers**, and an optional **Body**.



### A. The Request Line
The request line contains three fields separated by spaces:
* **HTTP Method (Verb):** Defines the exact action to be performed on the server.
  * `GET`: Requests data retrieval from a specified resource (No request body payload).
  * `POST`: Submits data to be processed to a specified resource (Data is packaged inside the request body).
  * `PUT`: Replaces all current representations of the target resource with the uploaded payload.
  * `DELETE`: Removes the specified resource from the server storage array.
* **Target URI (Path):** Specifies the absolute path to the resource on the server (e.g., `/images/logo.png` or `/index.html`).
* **HTTP Version:** Establishes the protocol version being spoken (typically `HTTP/1.1` or `HTTP/2`).

### 1. Comprehensive Core Request Headers (Client to Server)

| Request Header | Functional Working Mechanics | Technical/Security Context |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **`Host`** | Defines the target domain name and port number of the server. (Mandatory field in HTTP/1.1). | Enables **Virtual Hosting**, allowing one web server IP to serve multiple distinct web domains. |
| **`User-Agent`** | Contains a string detailing the client’s browser application, version, and host operating system type. | Frequently used in security forensics to trace automated attack scripts, scrapers, or bot fingerprints. |
| **`Accept`** | Informs the server about the media types (MIME types) the client browser is capable of processing (e.g., `text/html`). | Content negotiation. Prevents the server from sending payload data types the client cannot render. |
| **`Accept-Encoding`** | Signals which compression algorithms the client supports (e.g., `gzip`, `deflate`, `br`). | Maximizes bandwidth efficiency by allowing the server to compress payloads before transmission. |
| **`Accept-Language`** | Informs the server of the user's preferred human language preferences (e.g., `en-US`, `fr`). | Used by application backends to automatically serve localized structural text configurations. |
| **`Authorization`** | Carries the cryptographic credentials required to authenticate a client with a server (e.g., `Basic` base64 strings or `Bearer` tokens). | Highly sensitive target for packet interception; must never be passed over unencrypted HTTP channels. |
| **`Cookie`** | Automatically sends stored key-value state pairs back to the server that were previously set via the server's response stack. | The primary mechanism used to bypass HTTP's stateless design to track authenticated active sessions. |
| **`Connection`** | Controls whether the network socket remains open after the current transaction closes (e.g., `keep-alive`, `close`). | Directs TCP socket optimization rules to reduce handshaking overhead across rapid serial requests. |
| **`Content-Length`** | Declares the exact size of the request body payload in bytes (used in `POST` and `PUT` methods). | Necessary indicator so the receiving network stack knows exactly when the inbound data stream ends. |
| **`Content-Type`** | Discloses the media structure type of the resource payload located inside the request body (e.g., `application/json`). | Tells the server's backend framework parser how to unpack and read incoming request payloads. |
| **`Referer`** | Contains the absolute URL address of the previous web page from which a link to the current page was followed. | Used extensively for web analytics, traffic metrics tracking, and mapping navigation sequences. |

